00:46:46.830 --> 00:46:47.746
I absolutely hated it.

00:46:47.746 --> 00:46:49.670
I hated reading
about it constantly

00:46:49.670 --> 00:46:53.520
when I was sitting at
home, dead sober by myself.

00:46:53.520 --> 00:46:55.830
As for drugs, again,
there's a realistic reason

00:46:55.830 --> 00:46:58.674
why it might have a stigma.

00:46:58.674 --> 00:46:59.840
Because it can be dangerous.

00:46:59.840 --> 00:47:01.120
But your guess is
as good as mine.

00:47:01.120 --> 00:47:02.204
I mean, what do you think?

00:47:02.204 --> 00:47:03.828
That's not really a
scientific question

00:47:03.828 --> 00:47:04.910
as it is a political one.

00:47:04.910 --> 00:47:05.451
I don't know.

00:47:08.320 --> 00:47:08.972
I don't know.

00:47:12.828 --> 00:47:15.520
AUDIENCE: My question is sort
of connected with that one.

00:47:15.520 --> 00:47:17.264
Can you talk a little
bit about-- I'm

00:47:17.264 --> 00:47:18.830
sorry this is a
very broad question.

00:47:18.830 --> 00:47:21.330
Can you talk a little
bit about the connection

00:47:21.330 --> 00:47:23.693
between the science of drugs
and the criminalization

00:47:23.693 --> 00:47:25.234
and the more recent
decriminalization

00:47:25.234 --> 00:47:26.531
of some drugs.

00:47:26.531 --> 00:47:27.530
ZOE CORMIER: Yeah, sure.

00:47:27.530 --> 00:47:30.870
It's completely
nonsensical, and it's silly.

00:47:30.870 --> 00:47:32.840
I mean, the war on drugs
has obviously failed.

00:47:32.840 --> 00:47:35.110
Everybody knows
that it's failed.

00:47:35.110 --> 00:47:37.590
And the scientific basis
for what drugs are illegal

00:47:37.590 --> 00:47:40.120
and what drugs are not
illegal is not very sound.

00:47:40.120 --> 00:47:42.757
And the psychoactive
substances bill is ridiculous.

00:47:42.757 --> 00:47:44.590
I'm not sure if many
of you know about this,

00:47:44.590 --> 00:47:46.965
but the bill that they're
putting through where they want

00:47:46.965 --> 00:47:50.320
to make all legal highs,
except for tea, coffee,

00:47:50.320 --> 00:47:52.460
and alcohol, and tobacco.

00:47:52.460 --> 00:47:54.260
That's the only
handful of things

00:47:54.260 --> 00:47:55.718
that they're saying
that you should

00:47:55.718 --> 00:47:58.500
be able to buy over the counter
in any way, shape, or form.

00:47:58.500 --> 00:48:01.370
Technically, that would prohibit
you from smelling a rose.

00:48:01.370 --> 00:48:03.000
Technically it
would-- there have

00:48:03.000 --> 00:48:04.666
been lawyers who have
written about this

00:48:04.666 --> 00:48:07.030
in terms of the
neurological effects you

00:48:07.030 --> 00:48:09.960
get from other things
that produce pleasure.

00:48:09.960 --> 00:48:12.320
As to why they want to
clamp down on these things

00:48:12.320 --> 00:48:14.580
and why-- I mean, I understand
why they want to do it.

00:48:14.580 --> 00:48:17.420
Because they don't like the idea
of kids doing drugs in fields

00:48:17.420 --> 00:48:18.840
unattended.

00:48:18.840 --> 00:48:22.120
Why they think they'll be
successful is beyond me.

00:48:22.120 --> 00:48:23.870
There's no way that
this is going to work.

00:48:23.870 --> 00:48:25.231
Prohibition has never worked.

